 Who is Abe?  






Abe's Garden was named after Abram C. "Abe" Shmerling, M.D., a caring physician who concerned himself with the health and well-being of others, particularly the underserved. Dr. Shmerling was deeply invested in the people and community he loved. As a doctor of internal medicine, Dr. Shmerling committed his 45-year career to his patients and was especially dedicated to the economically disadvantaged. In 1952, he established one of Nashville's first fully integrated medical clinics, Woodbine Clinic, in one of the poorest areas of Nashville. He also worked with Dr. Thomas Frist, Sr., the Metro Council and community leaders in the late 1970s to locate a site for Southern Hills Hospital, where he served as its first chairman of the board, as well as on its founding medical staff.
After a long medical career serving the people of South Nashville, Alzheimer's disease began to rob Dr. Shmerling of who he was. With each passing year, Alzheimer's took something from him, however small, day-by-day and week-by-week for 11 years until his passing on November 4, 2006 at age 79.
He is survived by his wife, Frances; and sons, Jim, Michael and Rob; daughter, Judy; and 10 grandchildren.
After witnessing his father's experience, Michael D. Shmerling, Abe's middle son, has taken on a mission to create Abe's Garden, a nurturing and innovative campus in Nashville for individuals suffering from Alzheimer's disease and dementia. Use of the word “garden” is appropriate to describe this care community because many Alzheimer's residents like to wander, and Abe's Garden is being designed around a spacious, secure, well designed outdoor courtyard so residents may wander in their own special garden setting as Abe would have liked. 
 





 

 



Contact Us Today!

For more information about Abe's Garden or to schedule a tour, please contact us today!
Contact Us



Did You Know?

For every person diagnosed with Alzheimer’s disease there are 10 to 12 others – family, co-workers and neighbors – who are directly impacted.
Learn More



Evidence-Based

Low resident-to-caregiver partner ratio with innovative, evidence-based, continual quality improvement, staff training, programming and staffing models.




I see Abe's Garden becoming the leading American center in Alzheimer's care and contributing to research into the causes of Alzheimer's and other dementias.  It will be a leader in what is becoming a major medical problem, and I'm just glad we can help in some way.

– Jim Daniell



 








