        CONNECTTWEETLINKEDIN
                
                    5
                
            COMMENTEMAILMORENashville real estate investor Michael D. Shmerling and other family members are seeking a rezoning of nearly an acre at Pearl and Fisk streets with plans to build a pair of multifamily buildings with 50 one-bedroom residential units.With approval Wayne Enterprises — Shmerling's daughter Katie and her husband, Adam Wayne — could by year's end start construction of what the investor referred to as "affordable" apartments on the North Nashville site."There's definitely a need for more affordable housing in the neighborhood to compliment the high-end, which is the majority of residential units around there," Shmerling said, citing the Eleventh North luxury apartments at 11th and Charlotte as one example. "Our goal is for those to be half the price of the average facilities in the neighborhood, but they're small and they're modest, and they're not going to have swimming pools, tennis courts and wine cellars."The plan calls for monthly rents for the apartments to start at below $1,000, with about half of the units between $900 and $1,000, Shmerling added.Shmerling, chairman of XMi Holdings Inc., is no stranger to investing in real estate in the area where the land, which he owns, is located between Charlotte and Jo Johnston avenues. Nearly eight years ago, he bought the old Duck Head clothing manufacturing building on Charlotte Avenue and renovated it into an office and residential complex that's home to the Oasis Center, Big Brothers Big Sisters of Middle Tennessee and several other nonprofit organizations.XMi Property Management is expected to manage the apartments to be built on the site behind the parking lot for the Youth Opportunity Center complex, which those nonprofit groups occupy. The project site also sits across Pearl Street from Grace M. Eaton Childcare & Early Learning Center and is next to the Metro Development and Housing Agency's HOPE VI affordable housing.Shmerling is also one of Midtown Nashville's biggest property owners, even after selling off several holdings. Within the Church Street-Midtown corridor, he owns more than 300,000 square feet of multi-tenant office properties, plus several acres of land and standalone properties available for redevelopment.Reach Getahn Ward at 615-726-5968 and on Twitter @getahn.
            
